<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-633-233  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 633 233.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Nov 29 1990 n1565* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Braid Systems offers facsimile management system for local netusers. (Fax Messenger) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Braid Systems Ltd. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Fax Messenger (Office automation system) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSoftware PackagesFacsimileOffice Automation SoftwareElectronic Mail Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>BRAID SYSTEMS OFFERS FACSIMILE MANAGEMENTandM;SYSTEM FOR LOCAL NET USERSandM;London-based Braid Systems Ltd has launched messaging software to manageincoming and outgoing facsimile messages through a local area network.andO;Called Fax Messenger, the system enables users on an MS-DOS based network tocall up a list of recently arrived faxes, view any of them on screen andthen, if required, print out messages either on the nearest fax machine or ona laser printer.andP;  When sending a fax the user can type the message on-screen,using a word processing package or Braid's own editor, add an electronicsignature, then send it directly to the facsimile machine at the other end.andO;The system then tells the user if the fax has been transmitted or whether itcannot get through and the transmission has been aborted.andP;  Braid is mainlyaiming the system at medium to large sized companies with multiple lines anddistributed facsimile machines, perhaps spread across several floors.andP;  Aswell as speeding up the process of sending and receiving faxes, andeliminating problems of faxes going astray, Braid is selling the software asa complete &quot;fax management&quot; system.andP;  It has database facilities for filingincoming and outgoing documents, enabling organisations to track downdocuments months later or simply keep track of the facsimile costs to theorganisation.andP;  The faxes can also be archived onto optical disk for long-termstorage.andP;  However, managing the system requires a full-time operator to labelincoming faxes and then either route them to the correct fax machines to beprinted, enter them into a database for users throughout the organisations toretrieve or send a message to the appropriate user's personal computer to saythe fax has arrived.andP;  If the network is Novell NetWare-based, messages can besent straight to the bottom line of user's spreadsheets, otherwise the userhas to periodically check the shared database to see the faxes in the system.andO;Despite moves towards interoperability in X400 systems, for example IBM'sagreements with GE Information Services, MCI Communications US Sprint andATandamp;T, (CI No 1,521) Braid managing director Richard Little says that for themajority of users, this is the closest they will come to an externalelectronic messaging service for a long time.andP;  The pricing depends onconfiguration, and for 15 lines the cost is around #50,000.andO;</TEXT></DOC>